Ever wondered what it feels like to ruin people’s lives with overpriced and mediocre medication? Or perhaps you’re one of those that prefers saving lives to growing a bank account. Either way, your dream can now be a reality, or, well, a virtuality?

[i]Alcohol, tobacco, and pharmaceutical drugs are legal, but they can hurt a lot of people.

Ziggy Marley[/i]

Without any further delay, I present to you my review of Big Pharma.

[h1]Gameplay[/h1]
As a big time fan of management games, I couldn’t help but to take a look at Big Pharma, as it looked like it had everything it needed to be a great game. I couldn’t have been more wrong. It isn’t a great game. It’s a fantastic game. In reality, I should be playing right now, making some medication to cure everyone that doesn’t like the game.
Not only will Big Pharma test your personality, it will also test your ability to efficiently organize a factory. There aren’t any shareholders to please, but there’s always the need to be the best, and save everyone, or at least keep their wallets.
From preventing your opponents from producing a certain medication due to your patents, or even be stopped by your opponents with those same patents, to building massive lines that enable a super cure, you’ll find everything you need to have a good time right here.
There’s not much you can’t do in the game, except releasing diseases to help you improve your sales (there’s a suggestion right there!), so even if you’re having a bad day, you can always start the game and give all your customers bad blood pressure, or headaches, or anal leakage…
Bottom line is, Big Pharma is a fantastic management game, that offers some challenging scenarios, with some puzzle components, as well as need for a carefully planned development plan for the more challenging scenarios.


[h1]Pros[/h1]
[list][*] The scenarios provide tons of hours of entertainment;
[*] After spending a good number of hours with the scenarios, you’ll have some more fun with the sandbox, providing even more hours of entertainment;
[*] Customizable sandbox;
[*] The challenges are, indeed, challenging, and a good way to progressively learn the game;
[*] Some of the side-effects might cause perpetual laughter;
[*] Extensive technology and ingredients trees;
[*] The puzzle component of the game is also somewhat challenging, forcing the player to find the best way to save space as well as find the best combination for the line, in order to make more money;
[*] Wide variety of ingredients, equipment, side-effects, even floor patterns;
[*] The UI is very simple and easy to use;
[*] Ability to name your products, sounds simple, but it’s incredibly enjoyable;
[*] Despite not being an important part (for me at least), the graphics are pleasing;
[*] Modding - just imagine the possibilities;
[*] The developer is quite active on his forums.[/list]

There’s really nothing I can think of that’s negative per say, but, for those of you that might be somewhat perfectionists, there’s one small detail.

[h1]Cons[/h1]
[list][*] Some of the equipment doesn’t accurately portray reality.[/list]

[h1]Verdict[/h1]
I'd give it a [b]9.5/10[/b], which could easily be a 10, with one or two additions, such as being able to bankrupt opponents, or even release diseases to improve sales (yes, we all know it’s true).
